Here is a minimal `switchMap` pipeline. Every new `cityId$` emission cancels any pending `fetchWeather$` â€” `mergeMap` would race and let a stale response win.

```typescript
import { Observable } from "rxjs";
import { switchMap } from "rxjs/operators";

interface Weather {
  cityId: string;
  tempC: number;
  summary: string;
}

declare function fetchWeather$(cityId: string): Observable<Weather>;

export function weatherForSelection(
  cityId$: Observable<string>
): Observable<Weather> {
  return cityId$.pipe(
    switchMap((id: string): Observable<Weather> => fetchWeather$(id))
  );
}
```

`switchMap` unsubscribes from the previous inner observable on each new outer value â€” perfect for navigation where stale profiles must never overwrite the newest one.

```typescript
import { Observable } from "rxjs";
import { switchMap } from "rxjs/operators";

interface Profile {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  email: string;
}

declare function getProfile$(id: string): Observable<Profile>;

export function profileLoader(
  userId$: Observable<string>
): Observable<Profile> {
  return userId$.pipe(
    switchMap((id: string): Observable<Profile> => getProfile$(id))
  );
}
```

Use `switchMap` â€” it cancels the previous inner subscription on every new outer emission. A tiny pipeline:

```typescript
import { Observable } from "rxjs";
import { switchMap } from "rxjs/operators";

interface Hit {
  id: string;
  title: string;
}

declare function search$(q: string): Observable<Hit[]>;

export function latestResults(query$: Observable<string>): Observable<Hit[]> {
  return query$.pipe(
    switchMap((q: string): Observable<Hit[]> => search$(q))
  );
}
```

`switchMap` is the right operator: when `tenantId$` emits, the previous inner `loadDashboard$` is unsubscribed.

```typescript
import { Observable } from "rxjs";
import { switchMap } from "rxjs/operators";

interface Dashboard {
  tenantId: string;
  widgets: number;
}

declare function loadDashboard$(tenantId: string): Observable<Dashboard>;

export function dashboardStream(
  tenantId$: Observable<string>
): Observable<Dashboard> {
  return tenantId$.pipe(
    switchMap((id: string): Observable<Dashboard> => loadDashboard$(id))
  );
}
```

`switchMap` projects each outer value to an inner observable and **unsubscribes from the previous inner** when a new outer value arrives. That unsubscription is what cancels the in-flight HTTP request â€” the downstream subscriber only ever sees results for the newest input. Contrast with `mergeMap` (keeps all inner subscriptions alive) and `concatMap` (queues them). For route-driven fetches this is exactly the behaviour you want.

```typescript
import { Observable } from "rxjs";
import { switchMap } from "rxjs/operators";

interface Page {
  route: string;
  html: string;
}

declare function fetchPage$(route: string): Observable<Page>;

export function pageForRoute(route$: Observable<string>): Observable<Page> {
  return route$.pipe(
    switchMap((r: string): Observable<Page> => fetchPage$(r))
  );
}
```

Add cancellation-on-new-input to this v7 pipeline so the previous fetch is aborted when a new id arrives:

```typescript
import { Observable } from "rxjs";
import { mergeMap } from "rxjs/operators";
interface Doc { id: string; body: string }
declare function fetchDoc$(id: string): Observable<Doc>;
export function docStream(id$: Observable<string>): Observable<Doc> {
  return id$.pipe(mergeMap((id) => fetchDoc$(id)));
}
```

Swap `mergeMap` for `switchMap`. `mergeMap` lets every inner run in parallel â€” a late response can clobber a fresh one. `switchMap` unsubscribes the previous inner on each new id, which cancels the pending request.

```typescript
import { Observable } from "rxjs";
import { switchMap } from "rxjs/operators";

interface Doc {
  id: string;
  body: string;
}

declare function fetchDoc$(id: string): Observable<Doc>;

export function docStream(id$: Observable<string>): Observable<Doc> {
  return id$.pipe(
    switchMap((id: string): Observable<Doc> => fetchDoc$(id))
  );
}
```

`concatMap` subscribes to the next inner observable only after the previous one completes. Order is preserved end-to-end.

```typescript
import { Observable } from "rxjs";
import { concatMap } from "rxjs/operators";

interface UploadJob {
  id: string;
  bytes: number;
}
interface Receipt {
  jobId: string;
  url: string;
}

declare function upload$(job: UploadJob): Observable<Receipt>;

export function sequentialUploads(
  job$: Observable<UploadJob>
): Observable<Receipt> {
  return job$.pipe(
    concatMap((job: UploadJob): Observable<Receipt> => upload$(job))
  );
}
```

`concatMap` is the strict-order workhorse: it waits for each inner observable to complete before starting the next.

```typescript
import { Observable } from "rxjs";
import { concatMap } from "rxjs/operators";

interface Command {
  name: string;
  payload: string;
}
interface Ack {
  commandName: string;
  ok: boolean;
}

declare function runCommand$(cmd: Command): Observable<Ack>;

export function commandPipeline(
  command$: Observable<Command>
): Observable<Ack> {
  return command$.pipe(
    concatMap((cmd: Command): Observable<Ack> => runCommand$(cmd))
  );
}
```

Use `concatMap`. It enqueues each projection and subscribes to the next one only when the current completes.

```typescript
import { Observable } from "rxjs";
import { concatMap } from "rxjs/operators";

interface Task {
  id: string;
}
interface Result {
  taskId: string;
  output: string;
}

declare function run$(t: Task): Observable<Result>;

export function oneAtATime(task$: Observable<Task>): Observable<Result> {
  return task$.pipe(
    concatMap((t: Task): Observable<Result> => run$(t))
  );
}
```

`concatMap` buffers incoming outer emissions and projects them one at a time: it subscribes to an inner observable, waits for `complete`, then pulls the next outer value. That's why downstream order equals source order â€” no interleaving is possible. For a log writer this matters: line N+1 must never be flushed before line N.

```typescript
import { Observable } from "rxjs";
import { concatMap } from "rxjs/operators";

interface LogLine {
  ts: number;
  msg: string;
}

declare function writeLog$(line: LogLine): Observable<void>;

export function sequentialLogger(
  line$: Observable<LogLine>
): Observable<void> {
  return line$.pipe(
    concatMap((line: LogLine): Observable<void> => writeLog$(line))
  );
}
```

`concatMap` enforces FIFO and waits for completion. All projections are typed and `any` is banned.

```typescript
import { Observable } from "rxjs";
import { concatMap } from "rxjs/operators";

interface PaymentIntent {
  id: string;
  amountCents: number;
}
interface Settlement {
  intentId: string;
  confirmedAt: number;
}

declare function settle$(p: PaymentIntent): Observable<Settlement>;

export function settlementStream(
  intent$: Observable<PaymentIntent>
): Observable<Settlement> {
  return intent$.pipe(
    concatMap((p: PaymentIntent): Observable<Settlement> => settle$(p))
  );
}
```

Refactor this v7 pipeline so each job finishes before the next starts (currently they race):

```typescript
import { Observable } from "rxjs";
import { mergeMap } from "rxjs/operators";
interface Job { id: string }
interface Done { id: string }
declare function run$(j: Job): Observable<Done>;
export function p(j$: Observable<Job>): Observable<Done> {
  return j$.pipe(mergeMap((j) => run$(j)));
}
```

Swap `mergeMap` for `concatMap`. `concatMap` guarantees one-at-a-time, FIFO execution.

```typescript
import { Observable } from "rxjs";
import { concatMap } from "rxjs/operators";

interface Job {
  id: string;
}
interface Done {
  id: string;
}

declare function run$(j: Job): Observable<Done>;

export function p(j$: Observable<Job>): Observable<Done> {
  return j$.pipe(
    concatMap((j: Job): Observable<Done> => run$(j))
  );
}
```

`mergeMap(project, 4)` bounds in-flight inner subscriptions at 4. Unlike `concatMap` (1-at-a-time) and `switchMap` (cancels prior), `mergeMap` with a limit is the sweet spot for bounded parallelism.

```typescript
import { Observable } from "rxjs";
import { mergeMap } from "rxjs/operators";

interface ThumbJob {
  src: string;
}
interface Thumb {
  src: string;
  url: string;
}

declare function makeThumb$(job: ThumbJob): Observable<Thumb>;

export function thumbWorker(
  job$: Observable<ThumbJob>
): Observable<Thumb> {
  return job$.pipe(
    mergeMap((job: ThumbJob): Observable<Thumb> => makeThumb$(job), 4)
  );
}
```

`mergeMap(project, 3)` caps concurrency at three; results are interleaved in completion order, not source order.

```typescript
import { Observable } from "rxjs";
import { mergeMap } from "rxjs/operators";

interface Req {
  url: string;
}
interface Res {
  url: string;
  status: number;
}

declare function send$(r: Req): Observable<Res>;

export function parallelFetcher(
  req$: Observable<Req>
): Observable<Res> {
  return req$.pipe(
    mergeMap((r: Req): Observable<Res> => send$(r), 3)
  );
}
```

Pass a numeric concurrency argument to `mergeMap`. Results are interleaved but no more than 5 inners are ever active.

```typescript
import { Observable } from "rxjs";
import { mergeMap } from "rxjs/operators";

interface Task {
  id: number;
}
interface Out {
  id: number;
  ok: boolean;
}

declare function work$(t: Task): Observable<Out>;

export function boundedWorker(task$: Observable<Task>): Observable<Out> {
  return task$.pipe(
    mergeMap((t: Task): Observable<Out> => work$(t), 5)
  );
}
```

`switchMap` cancels the previous inner on each new outer â€” good for cancellation semantics (typeahead). `concatMap` queues and runs one at a time â€” good for strict ordering. `mergeMap(project, n)` allows up to `n` inners to run concurrently and interleaves results; it is the right tool when you want parallelism but not a stampede.

```typescript
import { Observable } from "rxjs";
import { mergeMap } from "rxjs/operators";

interface Url {
  href: string;
}
interface Fetched {
  href: string;
  size: number;
}

declare function fetch$(u: Url): Observable<Fetched>;

export function boundedFetcher(
  url$: Observable<Url>,
  concurrency: number
): Observable<Fetched> {
  return url$.pipe(
    mergeMap((u: Url): Observable<Fetched> => fetch$(u), concurrency)
  );
}
```

`mergeMap(project, 8)` bounds concurrency. The projection is explicitly typed â€” nothing leaks to `any`.

```typescript
import { Observable } from "rxjs";
import { mergeMap } from "rxjs/operators";

interface EmailJob {
  to: string;
  subject: string;
  body: string;
}
interface SendAck {
  to: string;
  messageId: string;
}

declare function sendEmail$(job: EmailJob): Observable<SendAck>;

export function emailFanout(
  job$: Observable<EmailJob>
): Observable<SendAck> {
  return job$.pipe(
    mergeMap((j: EmailJob): Observable<SendAck> => sendEmail$(j), 8)
  );
}
```

Add a concurrency cap of 4 to this unbounded RxJS v7 pipeline:

```typescript
import { Observable } from "rxjs";
import { mergeMap } from "rxjs/operators";
interface Pkg { name: string }
interface Result { name: string; ok: boolean }
declare function install$(p: Pkg): Observable<Result>;
export function installAll(p$: Observable<Pkg>): Observable<Result> {
  return p$.pipe(mergeMap((p) => install$(p)));
}
```

Add the `concurrent` argument (second positional arg to `mergeMap`) set to 4. That caps in-flight installs so the system doesn't get overwhelmed.

```typescript
import { Observable } from "rxjs";
import { mergeMap } from "rxjs/operators";

interface Pkg {
  name: string;
}
interface Result {
  name: string;
  ok: boolean;
}

declare function install$(p: Pkg): Observable<Result>;

export function installAll(p$: Observable<Pkg>): Observable<Result> {
  return p$.pipe(
    mergeMap((p: Pkg): Observable<Result> => install$(p), 4)
  );
}
```

`retry({ count, delay })` implements the backoff; `catchError` provides graceful degradation once retries are exhausted. Result: consumers never see an error â€” they get a safe default.

```typescript
import { Observable, of, timer } from "rxjs";
import { catchError, retry } from "rxjs/operators";

interface Item {
  id: string;
  name: string;
}

declare function fetchItems$(): Observable<Item[]>;

export function resilientItems(): Observable<Item[]> {
  return fetchItems$().pipe(
    retry({
      count: 3,
      delay: (_err: unknown, retryCount: number): Observable<number> =>
        timer(2 ** retryCount * 100),
    }),
    catchError((): Observable<Item[]> => of<Item[]>([]))
  );
}
```

`retry({ count: 2 })` covers transient failures; `catchError` maps the final error to a safe default so downstream never breaks.

```typescript
import { Observable, of } from "rxjs";
import { catchError, retry } from "rxjs/operators";

interface Flags {
  newNav: boolean;
  darkMode: boolean;
}

declare function fetchFlags$(): Observable<Flags>;

const DEFAULTS: Flags = { newNav: false, darkMode: false };

export function flagsWithFallback(): Observable<Flags> {
  return fetchFlags$().pipe(
    retry({ count: 2 }),
    catchError((): Observable<Flags> => of<Flags>(DEFAULTS))
  );
}
```

Use the config form of `retry`. The `delay` callback receives the error and the retry count (1-based) and must return an `Observable<unknown>` â€” `timer(ms)` is the standard choice. This replaces the deprecated `retryWhen`.

```typescript
import { Observable, timer } from "rxjs";
import { retry } from "rxjs/operators";

declare function call$(): Observable<string>;

export function retrying(): Observable<string> {
  return call$().pipe(
    retry({
      count: 4,
      delay: (_err: unknown, retryCount: number): Observable<number> =>
        timer(2 ** retryCount * 100),
    })
  );
}
```

Use `catchError` â€” it intercepts an error notification and lets you return a replacement `Observable<T>`.

```typescript
import { Observable, of } from "rxjs";
import { catchError } from "rxjs/operators";

interface Pref {
  theme: "light" | "dark";
}

declare function loadPrefs$(): Observable<Pref>;

const DEFAULT_PREF: Pref = { theme: "light" };

export function safePrefs(): Observable<Pref> {
  return loadPrefs$().pipe(
    catchError((): Observable<Pref> => of<Pref>(DEFAULT_PREF))
  );
}
```

`retry` resubscribes to the source on error up to `count` times with a configurable `delay`. Once retries are exhausted the error flows downstream, where `catchError` can map it to a safe fallback stream. Chained together you get: transient failures are absorbed by retries, persistent failures are surfaced as a typed default â€” consumers never have to handle raw errors.

```typescript
import { Observable, of, timer } from "rxjs";
import { catchError, retry } from "rxjs/operators";

interface Stats {
  users: number;
}

declare function fetchStats$(): Observable<Stats>;

export function safeStats(): Observable<Stats> {
  return fetchStats$().pipe(
    retry({
      count: 3,
      delay: (_err: unknown, retryCount: number): Observable<number> =>
        timer(2 ** retryCount * 200),
    }),
    catchError((): Observable<Stats> => of<Stats>({ users: 0 }))
  );
}
```

Linear backoff: delay `= retryCount * 200 ms`. Types are explicit on every callback.

```typescript
import { Observable, of, timer } from "rxjs";
import { catchError, retry } from "rxjs/operators";

interface Settings {
  locale: string;
  notifications: boolean;
}

declare function fetchSettings$(): Observable<Settings>;

const DEFAULT_SETTINGS: Settings = {
  locale: "en-US",
  notifications: true,
};

export function settingsWithFallback(): Observable<Settings> {
  return fetchSettings$().pipe(
    retry({
      count: 3,
      delay: (_err: unknown, retryCount: number): Observable<number> =>
        timer(retryCount * 200),
    }),
    catchError((): Observable<Settings> => of<Settings>(DEFAULT_SETTINGS))
  );
}
```

`takeUntil(destroy$)` completes the stream as soon as `destroy$` emits â€” no manual unsubscribe needed. `Subject<void>` is the canonical cleanup signal type.

```typescript
import { Observable, Subject, interval } from "rxjs";
import { map, takeUntil } from "rxjs/operators";

interface Tick {
  index: number;
  at: number;
}

export function pollUntilDestroyed(
  periodMs: number,
  destroy$: Subject<void>
): Observable<Tick> {
  return interval(periodMs).pipe(
    map((i: number): Tick => ({ index: i, at: Date.now() })),
    takeUntil(destroy$)
  );
}
```

All streams returned from the component should be piped through `takeUntil(destroy$)`. When the component tears down, the Subject emits once and every downstream subscription completes cleanly.

```typescript
import { Observable, Subject } from "rxjs";
import { takeUntil } from "rxjs/operators";

interface ServerEvent {
  kind: string;
  payload: string;
}

declare function serverEvents$(): Observable<ServerEvent>;

export function boundServerEvents(
  destroy$: Subject<void>
): Observable<ServerEvent> {
  return serverEvents$().pipe(takeUntil(destroy$));
}
```

Create a `Subject<void>` that the component calls `.next()` + `.complete()` on teardown, and pipe every long-lived observable through `takeUntil(destroy$)`. No manual `.unsubscribe()` is needed.

```typescript
import { Observable, Subject, interval } from "rxjs";
import { takeUntil } from "rxjs/operators";

export function heartbeat$(destroy$: Subject<void>): Observable<number> {
  return interval(1000).pipe(takeUntil(destroy$));
}
```

The `destroy$` pattern is the cleanest way to tie Observable lifetime to component (or scope) lifetime. You declare a `Subject<void>` once, pipe every long-lived stream through `takeUntil(destroy$)`, and on teardown call `destroy$.next(); destroy$.complete();`. Every subscription that was observing the source completes in one shot â€” no leaks, no bookkeeping of individual subscriptions.

```typescript
import { Observable, Subject } from "rxjs";
import { takeUntil } from "rxjs/operators";

interface ChatMsg {
  from: string;
  text: string;
}

declare function chatFeed$(roomId: string): Observable<ChatMsg>;

export function boundedChatFeed(
  roomId: string,
  destroy$: Subject<void>
): Observable<ChatMsg> {
  return chatFeed$(roomId).pipe(takeUntil(destroy$));
}
```

Fix this v7 snippet so it completes when `destroy$` emits instead of leaking forever:

```typescript
import { Observable, interval } from "rxjs";
export function ticks$(): Observable<number> {
  return interval(1000);
}
```

Take a `Subject<void>` parameter and pipe through `takeUntil(destroy$)` so the stream completes on teardown.

```typescript
import { Observable, Subject, interval } from "rxjs";
import { takeUntil } from "rxjs/operators";

export function ticks$(destroy$: Subject<void>): Observable<number> {
  return interval(1000).pipe(takeUntil(destroy$));
}
```

`defer` creates a fresh observable per subscriber. The factory runs on subscribe, so `Date.now()` is captured per-subscription â€” exactly what you want for side-effectful cold sources.

```typescript
import { Observable, defer, of } from "rxjs";

interface Stamp {
  at: number;
}

export const stamp$: Observable<Stamp> = defer(
  (): Observable<Stamp> => of<Stamp>({ at: Date.now() })
);
```

Without `defer`, the Promise would be created once at factory time and shared across subscriptions â€” no re-fetch. `defer` invokes the factory per subscribe, so each subscriber gets a fresh Promise.

```typescript
import { Observable, defer, from } from "rxjs";

interface Token {
  value: string;
  expiresAt: number;
}

declare function mintToken(): Promise<Token>;

export const token$: Observable<Token> = defer(
  (): Observable<Token> => from(mintToken())
);
```

Wrap the factory in `defer`. The function runs on each subscribe, which re-executes whatever side effect the factory performs.

```typescript
import { Observable, defer, of } from "rxjs";

let counter = 0;

export const next$: Observable<number> = defer(
  (): Observable<number> => of<number>(++counter)
);
```

An observable built with `of` or `from(promise)` captures its value **at construction time**. `defer` flips that: it invokes a factory **at subscription time**, so any closed-over side effect (current time, random id, fresh Promise) is computed per subscriber. Critical for polling patterns and per-subscriber Promise creation.

```typescript
import { Observable, defer, of } from "rxjs";

interface Sample {
  ts: number;
}

export const sample$: Observable<Sample> = defer(
  (): Observable<Sample> => of<Sample>({ ts: performance.now() })
);
```

`defer` gives each subscriber a new factory invocation, which lets us mint a fresh id â€” closure state + `defer` is the idiom.

```typescript
import { Observable, defer, of } from "rxjs";

let seq = 0;

interface RequestId {
  id: string;
}

export const requestId$: Observable<RequestId> = defer(
  (): Observable<RequestId> => of<RequestId>({ id: `req-${++seq}` })
);
```

`tap` is for mid-stream observation (per next/error/complete). `finalize` fires exactly once when the subscription terminates â€” on complete, error, **or** unsubscribe. Perfect for releasing loading-spinner state.

```typescript
import { Observable } from "rxjs";
import { finalize, tap } from "rxjs/operators";

interface Payload {
  ok: boolean;
}

declare function call$(): Observable<Payload>;

export function loggedCall(): Observable<Payload> {
  return call$().pipe(
    tap({
      next: (v: Payload): void => console.log("next", v),
      error: (e: unknown): void => console.log("error", e),
      complete: (): void => console.log("complete"),
    }),
    finalize((): void => console.log("done"))
  );
}
```

`BehaviorSubject<boolean>` is a tiny state holder. We flip it on inside `tap({ subscribe })` â€” no such hook exists, so instead we set it **before** returning the pipeline, and clear it in `finalize`. A typed helper keeps ergonomics clean.

```typescript
import { BehaviorSubject, Observable, defer } from "rxjs";
import { finalize } from "rxjs/operators";

interface Row {
  id: number;
}

declare function load$(): Observable<Row[]>;

export const loading$ = new BehaviorSubject<boolean>(false);

export function loadWithSpinner$(): Observable<Row[]> {
  return defer((): Observable<Row[]> => {
    loading$.next(true);
    return load$().pipe(
      finalize((): void => loading$.next(false))
    );
  });
}
```

`finalize` â€” it fires exactly once when the subscription ends, regardless of whether the end was `complete`, `error`, or an external unsubscribe.

```typescript
import { Observable } from "rxjs";
import { finalize } from "rxjs/operators";

declare function fetchRows$(): Observable<number[]>;

export function rowsWithCleanup(): Observable<number[]> {
  return fetchRows$().pipe(
    finalize((): void => console.log("cleanup"))
  );
}
```

Pass an object with `next`, `error`, `complete` handlers to `tap`. The positional form is deprecated in v7.

```typescript
import { Observable } from "rxjs";
import { tap } from "rxjs/operators";

declare function source$(): Observable<number>;

export function logged$(): Observable<number> {
  return source$().pipe(
    tap({
      next: (v: number): void => console.log("next", v),
      error: (e: unknown): void => console.log("error", e),
      complete: (): void => console.log("complete"),
    })
  );
}
```

`tap` is an observation operator: for every notification (next/error/complete) its matching handler runs, and the notification is passed through unchanged. `finalize` is a teardown hook: it runs **once**, on any termination of the subscription â€” complete, error, or unsubscribe. Rule of thumb: use `tap` to observe values, use `finalize` to release resources.

```typescript
import { Observable } from "rxjs";
import { finalize, tap } from "rxjs/operators";

interface Row {
  id: string;
}

declare function rows$(): Observable<Row[]>;

export function observed$(): Observable<Row[]> {
  return rows$().pipe(
    tap({
      next: (rs: Row[]): void => console.log("rows", rs.length),
      error: (e: unknown): void => console.log("err", e),
      complete: (): void => console.log("done-notification"),
    }),
    finalize((): void => console.log("resource-released"))
  );
}
```

`tap({ next, error, complete })` logs; `finalize` runs on complete **or** error **or** unsubscribe â€” exactly once â€” perfect for clearing a loading flag.

```typescript
import { BehaviorSubject, Observable } from "rxjs";
import { finalize, tap } from "rxjs/operators";

interface Resource {
  id: string;
  data: string;
}

declare function fetchResource$(id: string): Observable<Resource>;

export const loading$ = new BehaviorSubject<boolean>(false);

export function fetchWithFlag$(id: string): Observable<Resource> {
  loading$.next(true);
  return fetchResource$(id).pipe(
    tap({
      next: (r: Resource): void => console.log("got", r.id),
      error: (e: unknown): void => console.log("err", e),
      complete: (): void => console.log("done"),
    }),
    finalize((): void => loading$.next(false))
  );
}
```
